paragraphs.text: %md ## Classification Modeling to Predict Target Customers using Random Forest Oracle Machine Learning for R (OML4R) makes the open source R scripting language and environment ready for the enterprise and big data. Designed for problems involving both large and small data volumes, OML4R integrates R with Oracle Autonomous Database, allowing users to run R commands and scripts for statistical, machine learning, and visualization analyses on database tables and views using R syntax. Many familiar R functions are overloaded that translate R behavior into SQL for running in-database. In this notebook, we highlight the Random Forest algorithm for classification in OML4R and predict customers most likely to be positive responders to an Affinity Card loyalty program. High Affinity Card responders (target value = 1) are defined as those customers who, when given a loyalty or affinity card, hyper-respond, that is, increase purchases more than the Affinity Card program's offered discount. This notebook builds and applies a classification random forest model using the Sales History (SH) schema data. All processing occurs inside Oracle Autonomous Database. msg.data:
Classification Modeling to Predict Target Customers using Random Forest

Oracle Machine Learning for R (OML4R) makes the open source R scripting language and environment ready for the enterprise and big data. Designed for problems involving both large and small data volumes, OML4R integrates R with Oracle Autonomous Database, allowing users to run R commands and scripts for statistical, machine learning, and visualization analyses on database tables and views using R syntax. Many familiar R functions are overloaded that translate R behavior into SQL for running in-database.

In this notebook, we highlight the Random Forest algorithm for classification in OML4R and predict customers most likely to be positive responders to an Affinity Card loyalty program.

High Affinity Card responders (target value = 1) are defined as those customers who, when given a loyalty or affinity card, hyper-respond, that is, increase purchases more than the Affinity Card program's offered discount.

This notebook builds and applies a classification random forest model using the Sales History (SH) schema data. All processing occurs inside Oracle Autonomous Database.

%r

DEMO_DF <- SUP_DEM[,c("CUST_ID", 'AFFINITY_CARD', "BOOKKEEPING_APPLICATION", "BULK_PACK_DISKETTES", "EDUCATION", 
                      "FLAT_PANEL_MONITOR", "HOME_THEATER_PACKAGE", "HOUSEHOLD_SIZE", "OCCUPATION", "OS_DOC_SET_KANJI", 
                      "PRINTER_SUPPLIES", "YRS_RESIDENCE", "Y_BOX_GAMES")]

paragraphs.title: Create train and test data (60/40 split)
paragraphs.text:
%r

sampleSize <- 600
index <- sample(1:nrow(SUP_DEM),sampleSize)
group <- as.integer(1:nrow(SUP_DEM) %in% index)

paragraphs.title: Create train and test data sets
paragraphs.text:
%r

set.seed(123)
rownames(DEMO_DF) <- DEMO_DF$CUST_ID

sampleSize <- .6 * nrow(DEMO_DF)
index <- sample(1:nrow(DEMO_DF),sampleSize)

# Create training data set
DEMO_DF.train <- DEMO_DF[index,]

# Create test data set
DEMO_DF.test <- DEMO_DF[setdiff(1:nrow(DEMO_DF),index),]

class(DEMO_DF.train)
cat("\nTraining data: ")
dim(DEMO_DF.train)

class(DEMO_DF.test)
cat("\nTest data: ")
dim(DEMO_DF.test)

%md
## Build a Random Forest Model using Default settings

msg.data: Build a Random Forest Model using Default settings

paragraphs.text:
%r

MOD <- ore.odmRF(AFFINITY_CARD~., DEMO_DF)     
#tree10 <- grabTree(MOD, k = 10, labelVar = TRUE) 

RES <- predict(MOD, DEMO_DF, type=c("class","raw"), supplemental.cols= "AFFINITY_CARD")

paragraphs.title: Confusion Matrix
paragraphs.text:
%r

C_MATRIX <- with(RES, table(AFFINITY_CARD, PREDICTION))   
C_MATRIX

paragraphs.title: Show model accuracy
paragraphs.text:
%r

ACCURACY <- C_MATRIX/sum(C_MATRIX)
round(sum(diag(ACCURACY)),3)

%md ### Examples of possible setting overrides for Random Forest If the user does not override the default settings, then relevant settings are determined by the algorithm A complete list of settings can be found in the Documentation link: -- Algorithm Settings: Random Forest -- Shared Settings: All Algorithms -- Specify a row weight column 'ODMS_ROW_WEIGHT_COLUMN_NAME' = '' -- Specify a missing value treatment method. The default is to replace with mean (numeric features), mode (categorical features) or delete the row 'ODMS_MISSING_VALUE_TREATMENT' = 'ODMS_MISSING_VALUE_DELETE_ROW' -- Specify the number of trees in the forest. It requires a number between 1 and 65535 (including the edges). The default is 20. 'RFOR_NUM_TREES' = '20' -- Specify the fraction of the training data to be randomly sampled for use in the construction of an individual tree. The default is half of the number of rows in the training data. It requires a fraction between 0 and 1 (excluding the edges) 'RFOR_SAMPLING_RATIO' = '0.5' -- Specify the size of the random subset of columns to be considered when choosing a split at a node. For each node, the size of the pool remains the same, but the specific candidate columns change. The default is half of the columns in the model signature. The special value 0 indicates that the candidate pool includes all columns. It requires a number equal to or greater than 0. 'RFOR_MTRY' = '0'

msg.data:
Examples of possible setting overrides for Random Forest

If the user does not override the default settings, then relevant settings are determined by the algorithm

A complete list of settings can be found in the Documentation link:

– Algorithm Settings: Random Forest

– Shared Settings: All Algorithms

– Specify a row weight column

'ODMS_ROW_WEIGHT_COLUMN_NAME' = '<row_weight_column_name>'

– Specify a missing value treatment method. The default is to replace with mean (numeric features), mode (categorical features) or delete the row

'ODMS_MISSING_VALUE_TREATMENT' = 'ODMS_MISSING_VALUE_DELETE_ROW'

– Specify the number of trees in the forest. It requires a number between 1 and 65535 (including the edges). The default is 20.

'RFOR_NUM_TREES' = '20'

– Specify the fraction of the training data to be randomly sampled for use in the construction of an individual tree. The default is half of the number of rows in the training data. It requires a fraction between 0 and 1 (excluding the edges)

'RFOR_SAMPLING_RATIO' = '0.5'

– Specify the size of the random subset of columns to be considered when choosing a split at a node. For each node, the size of the pool remains the same, but the specific candidate columns change. The default is half of the columns in the model signature. The special value 0 indicates that the candidate pool includes all columns. It requires a number equal to or greater than 0.

'RFOR_MTRY' = '0'

paragraphs.title: Build a Random Forest Model using Explicit settings
paragraphs.text:
%r

ore.exec("BEGIN DBMS_DATA_MINING.DROP_MODEL(model_name=> 'RF_CLASSIFICATION_MODEL'); EXCEPTION WHEN others THEN null; END;")

settings = list(RFOR_MTRY = 3, 
                RFOR_NUM_TREES = 100, 
                RFOR_SAMPLING_RATIO =0.5,
                model_name="RF_CLASSIFICATION_MODEL")

MOD2 <- ore.odmRF(AFFINITY_CARD~., DEMO_DF.train, odm.settings= settings)


RES2 <- predict(MOD2, DEMO_DF.test, type= c("class","raw"), norm.votes=TRUE, cache.model=TRUE, 
                supplemental.cols=c("CUST_ID", "AFFINITY_CARD", "BOOKKEEPING_APPLICATION", "BULK_PACK_DISKETTES", 
                                    "EDUCATION", "FLAT_PANEL_MONITOR", "HOME_THEATER_PACKAGE", "HOUSEHOLD_SIZE", 
                                    "OCCUPATION", "OS_DOC_SET_KANJI", "PRINTER_SUPPLIES", "YRS_RESIDENCE", "Y_BOX_GAMES"))

msg.data:
Warning message:
“The created mining model RF_CLASSIFICATION_MODEL is explicitly named. ORE does not manage this mining model's life cycle.”

paragraphs.text:

C_MATRIX2 <- with(RES2, table(AFFINITY_CARD, PREDICTION))  
C_MATRIX2

paragraphs.text:
%r

ACCURACY2 <- C_MATRIX2/sum(C_MATRIX2)
round(sum(diag(ACCURACY2)),3)

%md
## Display ROC Curve, Lift Chart, and Distribution Chart

msg.data: Display ROC Curve, Lift Chart, and Distribution Chart

paragraphs.text:
%r

# BAR PLOT
res <- ore.pull(RES)
sensitivity <- res[order(res$"'1'",decreasing = TRUE), ]
sens <- sum(sensitivity$"'0'")/sum(sensitivity$"'0'") - cumsum(sensitivity$"'0'")/sum(sensitivity$"'0'")
spec <- cumsum(sensitivity$"'1'")/sum(sensitivity$"'1'")

# LIFT CHART
decile2 <- quantile(sensitivity$"'1'", probs = seq(.1, .9, by = .1))
df_sens <- as.data.frame(sensitivity$"'1'", col.names = c("sens"))
df_sens$decile = as.numeric(cut(1-cumsum(df_sens$sens), breaks=10))


# DISTRIBUTION CHART
dx <- density(res$"'0'")
dx2 <- density(res$"'1'")

# PLOTS 3x1
par(mfrow=c(3,3))
plot(1 - spec, sens, type = "l", col = "darkred", ylab = "Sensitivity", xlab = "1 - Specificity", main = 'ROC Curve')
abline(c(0,0),c(1,1))
paste("AUC: ", round(sum(spec*diff(c(0, 1 - sens))),3)) 

barplot(table(df_sens$decile), xlab = 'Decile', ylab = 'Actual Targets', main = 'Lift Chart', col = "darkred")

plot(dx, lwd = 2, col = "burlywood",
     main = "Density")
lines(dx2, lwd = 2, col = "darkred")
# Add the data-poins with noise in the X-axis
rug(jitter(res$"'0'"),col='burlywood')
rug(jitter(res$"'1'"),col='darkred')

paragraphs.title: Create table for use in SQL query
paragraphs.text:
%r

ore.drop(table = "RF_TEST_TABLE")
ore.create(DEMO_DF, table ="RF_TEST_TABLE")

paragraphs.title: Demonstrate using the SQL interface so score data and display prediction details
paragraphs.text:
%sql

SELECT CUST_ID,
    round(PREDICTION_YRS_RES,3) PRED_YRS_RES,
    RTRIM(TRIM(SUBSTR(OUTPRED."Attribute1",17,100)),'rank="1"/>') FIRST_ATTRIBUTE,
    RTRIM(TRIM(SUBSTR(OUTPRED."Attribute2",17,100)),'rank="2"/>') SECOND_ATTRIBUTE,
    RTRIM(TRIM(SUBSTR(OUTPRED."Attribute3",17,100)),'rank="3"/>') THIRD_ATTRIBUTE
FROM (SELECT CUST_ID,
             PREDICTION(RF_CLASSIFICATION_MODEL USING *) PREDICTION_YRS_RES,
             PREDICTION_DETAILS(RF_CLASSIFICATION_MODEL USING *) PD
      FROM RF_TEST_TABLE
      WHERE CUST_ID < 100015
      ORDER BY CUST_ID) OUT,
               XMLTABLE('/Details'
                        PASSING OUT.PD
                        COLUMNS 
                        "Attribute1" XMLType PATH 'Attribute[1]',
                        "Attribute2" XMLType PATH 'Attribute[2]',
                        "Attribute3" XMLType PATH 'Attribute[3]')  OUTPRED
